PRISMA, a space-borne hyperspectral sensor developed by the Italian Space Agency (ASI), can capture images in a continuum of 231 spectral bands ranging between 400400400400 and 2500250025002500 nm, at a spatial resolution of 30 m. The method was applied to a PRISMA Bottom-Of-Atmosphere (BOA) reflectance scene of the Quadril√°tero Ferr√≠fero area (Minas Gerias State, Brazil), located in the central portion of the Minas Gerais State (Northern Brazil). 
The PRISMA hyperspectral image shows a reflectance scene at the Bottom-Of-Atmosphere (BOA) of the Quadril√°tero Ferr√≠fero mining district. It was acquired on May 21, 2022, at 13:05:52 UTC.
Level 2C PRISMA hyperspectral imagery was accessed from the mission website http://prisma.asi.it/. The VNIR and SWIR datacubes were pre-processed using tools available in ENVI 5.6.1 (L3Harris Technologies, USA). Errors in absolute geolocation were corrected using the Refine RPCs (HDF-EOS5) task, included within the PRISMA Toolkit in ENVI.
Only 193 out of 231 bands were used for the final image due to atmospheric absorption affecting the excluded bands.

The ESA WorldCover-Map, available at https://esa-worldcover.org/en, was used in conjunction with the Global-scale mining polygons (Version 1) [14] to establish the ground truth for the Brazilian region. In order to avoid redundant and noisy information, only the following features were selected: vegetation (including dense, sparse, and very sparse vegetation as well as crops), water areas, mining areas, and build-up areas. As it can be seen from Table 3, the vegetation class in the image is over-represented. To address this issue, a random selection of 700,000700000700,000700 , 000 vegetation pixels are set to 0 (undefined class). This adjustment ensures that the number of vegetation class pixels is comparable with the other classes. This is illustrated in Fig. 4.

To evaluate the effectiveness of this method in classifying hyperspectral remote sensing images, we made a comparison with four mainstream methods: SVD/Unet [19], HSI-CNN [20], 3D-CNN [21] and contextual deep CNN [22]. It‚Äôs important to note that not all experiments involve pixel-by-pixel classification (or semantic segmentation). Only SVD/Unet, contextual deep CNN, and AMBER use this approach. On the other hand, HSI-CNN and 3D-CNN perform pure image classification, where the classes are determined by the centroid of the patch. This results in an increase in the metrics. Despite this, AMBER shows better results compared to the other methods on the Indian Pines dataset and Pavia University dataset and comparable results on the PRISMA dataset.

In the SVD/Unet method, the spectral dimension of the image is first reduced by a Singular Value Decomposition, considering only the first three singular values, and then a Unet architecture is used to classify pixels. This method has shown promising results in the semantic segmentation of PRISMA hyperspectral images.

In the HSI-CNN, the spectral-spatial features are first extracted from a target pixel and its neighbors. Next, several one-dimensional feature maps are obtained by performing a convolution operation on the spectral-spatial features, and these maps are then stacked into a two-dimensional matrix. Finally, this two-dimensional matrix, treated as an image, is input into a standard CNN.

The 3D-CNN architecture is a Multiscale 3D deep convolutional neural network (M3D-DCNN) which could jointly learn both 2D Multi-scale spatial feature and 1D spectral feature from HSI data in an end-to-end approach.

The contextual deep CNN first concurrently applies multiple 3-dimensional local convolutional filters with different sizes jointly exploiting spatial and spectral features of a hyperspectral image. The initial spatial and spectral feature maps obtained from applying the variable size convolutional filters are then combined together to form a joint spatio-spectral feature map. The joint feature map representing rich spectral and spatial properties of the hyperspectral image is then fed through fully convolutional layers that eventually predict the corresponding label of each pixel vector.

Every neural network mentioned above was trained on the same patches using the configuration described in the corresponding papers [19] [20] [21] [22]. ‚ÄúSame patches‚Äù in this context refers to patches that have identical centroids. AMBER was trained on patches of dimension D√ó32√ó32ùê∑3232D\times 32\times 32italic_D √ó 32 √ó 32 where D is the spectral dimension, as previously mentioned. SVD/UNet was trained on patches of 3√ó32√ó32332323\times 32\times 323 √ó 32 √ó 32 where 3 is the number of singular values. HSI-CNN was trained using patches of D√ó3√ó3ùê∑33D\times 3\times 3italic_D √ó 3 √ó 3, 3D-CNN using D√ó7√ó7ùê∑77D\times 7\times 7italic_D √ó 7 √ó 7 patches, and contextual deep CNN using D√ó5√ó5ùê∑55D\times 5\times 5italic_D √ó 5 √ó 5 patches (D is, again, the spectral dimension).
For every method, we conducted 5 experiments for each dataset. The classification accuracy of different methods on the three data sets is presented in Tables 4, 5, and 6, with the highest values highlighted in bold font. A comprehensive comparative analysis is presented to draw conclusions.

The Overall Accuracy (OA), Kappa coefficients, and Average Accuracy (AA) of the AMBER method, calculated across 5 different experiments, are higher than those of the compared methods on both the Indian Pines dataset and the Pavia University dataset.
On the Indian Pines dataset, the method achieved an OA of 99.74%, a Kappa coefficient of 0.9968, and an AA of 99.18%, representing a significant improvement compared to the other methods. In particular, AMBER demonstrates the ability to detect classes with few representations, such as class 7 (Grass-pasture-mowed), which has only 28 pixels. Other methods, such as SVD/Unet or HSI-CNN, struggle to detect this class, resulting in an accuracy per class of 0% .
Another important feature is that, compared to other methods (especially SVD/Unet), AMBER has a very low standard deviation for OA, Kappa coefficient, and AA. This indicates a good ability to generalize: the results do not seem to depend on how the training data are chosen.

For the Pavia University dataset, the OA reached 99.94%, the Kappa coefficient reached 0.9991 and the AA reached 99.82%, mantaining an high accuracy on all the classes. As the Indian Pines dataset, AMBER has a very low standard deviation for OA, Kappa coefficient, and AA. 
For the PRISMA dataset, the AMBER model achieved an Overall Accuracy of 90.90%, a Kappa coefficient of 0.8741, and an Average Accuracy of 90.92. While this result is slightly lower than the SVD/Unet method, it outperformed the other methods. Furthermore, the lower performances of AMBER on the PRISMA dataset are under investigation.
AMBER is also able to improve the classification accuracy of a variety of features, such as Alfalfa, Grass-pasture-mowed and Soybean-mintill in the Indian Pines dataset; Asphalt, Gravel and Bitumen in the Pavia University dataset; mining area and build-up in the PRISMA dataset. This method is also able to perform segmentation on different types of hyperspectral images, maintaining high accuracy on both airborne (Pavia University and Indian Pines) and spaceborne (PRISMA) hyperspectral images.

The Fig. 5, 6, and 7 show the false color image (a), the ground truth sample plots (b), and the AMBER classification result plots (c) and (d). Specifically, plot (c) is the predicted result (d) with an additional mask of the ground truth undefined pixels applied a posteriori to visually justify the high accuracy for all types of features presented in Tables 4, 5 and 6. Specifically, on the Pavia University dataset and the Indian Pines dataset, the ground truth (b) and the prediction (c) are nearly identical, as expected.

Fig. 8 shows that AMBER accurately predicts the pixels classified as undefined in the ground-truth map (which are not used in the loss function computation). The figure shows an example of how AMBER can also segment complex structures. This particular structure belongs to the asphalt class in the Pavia University dataset.

To evaluate the effectiveness of this method in classifying hyperspectral remote sensing images, we made a comparison with four mainstream methods: SVD/Unet [19], HSI-CNN [20], 3D-CNN [21] and contextual deep CNN [22]. It‚Äôs important to note that not all experiments involve pixel-by-pixel classification (or semantic segmentation). Only SVD/Unet, contextual deep CNN, and AMBER use this approach. On the other hand, HSI-CNN and 3D-CNN perform pure image classification, where the classes are determined by the centroid of the patch. This results in an increase in the metrics. Despite this, AMBER shows better results compared to the other methods on the Indian Pines dataset and Pavia University dataset and comparable results on the PRISMA dataset.

In the SVD/Unet method, the spectral dimension of the image is first reduced by a Singular Value Decomposition, considering only the first three singular values, and then a Unet architecture is used to classify pixels. This method has shown promising results in the semantic segmentation of PRISMA hyperspectral images.

In the HSI-CNN, the spectral-spatial features are first extracted from a target pixel and its neighbors. Next, several one-dimensional feature maps are obtained by performing a convolution operation on the spectral-spatial features, and these maps are then stacked into a two-dimensional matrix. Finally, this two-dimensional matrix, treated as an image, is input into a standard CNN.

The 3D-CNN architecture is a Multiscale 3D deep convolutional neural network (M3D-DCNN) which could jointly learn both 2D Multi-scale spatial feature and 1D spectral feature from HSI data in an end-to-end approach.

The contextual deep CNN first concurrently applies multiple 3-dimensional local convolutional filters with different sizes jointly exploiting spatial and spectral features of a hyperspectral image. The initial spatial and spectral feature maps obtained from applying the variable size convolutional filters are then combined together to form a joint spatio-spectral feature map. The joint feature map representing rich spectral and spatial properties of the hyperspectral image is then fed through fully convolutional layers that eventually predict the corresponding label of each pixel vector.

Every neural network mentioned above was trained on the same patches using the configuration described in the corresponding papers [19] [20] [21] [22]. ‚ÄúSame patches‚Äù in this context refers to patches that have identical centroids. AMBER was trained on patches of dimension D√ó32√ó32ùê∑3232D\times 32\times 32italic_D √ó 32 √ó 32 where D is the spectral dimension, as previously mentioned. SVD/UNet was trained on patches of 3√ó32√ó32332323\times 32\times 323 √ó 32 √ó 32 where 3 is the number of singular values. HSI-CNN was trained using patches of D√ó3√ó3ùê∑33D\times 3\times 3italic_D √ó 3 √ó 3, 3D-CNN using D√ó7√ó7ùê∑77D\times 7\times 7italic_D √ó 7 √ó 7 patches, and contextual deep CNN using D√ó5√ó5ùê∑55D\times 5\times 5italic_D √ó 5 √ó 5 patches (D is, again, the spectral dimension).
For every method, we conducted 5 experiments for each dataset. The classification accuracy of different methods on the three data sets is presented in Tables 4, 5, and 6, with the highest values highlighted in bold font. A comprehensive comparative analysis is presented to draw conclusions.

In particular, AMBER demonstrates the ability to detect classes with few representations, such as class 7 (Grass-pasture-mowed), which has only 28 pixels. Other methods, such as SVD/Unet or HSI-CNN, struggle to detect this class, resulting in an accuracy per class of 0% .
